olina]] ([[Asociaci\u00f3n del F\u00fatbol Argentino|Argentina]])\n<includeonly>|}</includeonly><section end=Lineups />\n| width=50% valign=top|\n'''Match Rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of [[extra time]] if necessary.\n*Penalty shoot-out if scores still level.\n*Two [[substitute (football)|substitutions]] permitted, plus one for the goalkeeper.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n[[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Al Gore]], [[List of Presidents of UEFA|UEFA president]] [[Lennart Johansson]], and [[List of presidents of FIFA|FIFA president]] [[Jo\u00e3o Havelange]] were among those present at the stands during the awards ceremony. Vice President Gore handed the trophy to Brazilian captain [[Dunga]].<ref name=\"coming\"/><ref>{{YouTube |pLPM_JSbGvI|Brazil v Italy - The Final - 1994 FIFA World Cup USA\u2122}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Brazil\u2013Italy football rivalry]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{1994 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Brazil national football team matches}}\n{{Italy national football team matches}}\n{{Portal bar|Association football|Greater Los Angeles|1990s|Brazil|Italy}}\n\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup finals|1994]]\n[[Category:Brazil national football team matches|1994]]\n[[Category:Italy national football team matches|1994]]\n[[Category:1994 FIFA World Cup|1]]\n[[Category:Brazil at the 1994 FIFA World Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Association football penalty shoot-outs|Fifa World Cup Final 1994]]\n[[Category:Brazil\u2013Italy relations]]\n[[Category:Italy at the 1994 FIFA World Cup|Final]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in California]]\n[[Category:1994 in sports in California]]\n[[Category:20th century in Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:July 1994 sports events in the United States|FIFA World Cup final]]\n", "name_user": "188.69.223.235", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1994_FIFA_World_Cup_Final"}
{"title_page": "Multilingualism in Luxembourg", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2012}}\n[[Multilingualism]] is a part of everyday life for the population of [[Luxembourg]]. Legally and socially, different sectors of Luxembourg use [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], and [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]], which is a variety of [[Moselle Franconian dialects|Moselle Franconian]] with a large number of loanwords from French. Additionally, most citizens learn [[English language|English]] and may study other languages as well. A substantial immigrant population has brought numerous [[immigrant language]]s to the small state, notably [[Portuguese Luxembourger|Portuguese, which is spoken by more than one-fifth of the population]]. However, the different languages are used in different social situations.\n\n==Official languages==\nThe use of languages for legal and administrative purposes is regulated by a law promulgated in 1984, including the following provisions:<ref>{{in lang|fr}} ''M\u00e9morial A'' no. 16 (27 February 1984), pp. 196\u2013197: [http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1984/0162702/index.html \"Loi du 24 f\u00e9vrier 1984 sur le r\u00e9gime des langues\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060203005510/http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1984/0162702/index.html |date=2006-02-03 }}</ref>\n\n* Article 1: The national language of the Luxembourgers is [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]].\n* Article 2: The laws are in [[French language|French]].\n* Article 3: The language of the government: Luxembourgish, [[German language|German]] and French can be used.\n* Article 4: Administrative questions: If a citizen asks a question in Luxembourgish, German or French, the administration must reply, as far as possible, in the language in which the question was asked.\n\nIn many other multilingual countries, such as [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]] and [[Canada]], the distribution of the languages is geographic, but in Luxembourg it is functional\u2014that is, the choice of language depends on the situation.\n\n==Education==\nAt school, all students are taught in all three official languages, although divided by age group and subject matter.  At [[primary school]], the courses are taught in German and explanations are often given in Luxembourgish.  In general, at [[secondary school]], up until the 9th grade, every subject is taught in German, except for mathematics and sciences (which are taught in French). From 10th to 13th grade, the language use depends on what level the students are in: In the more difficult level, as well as at the commerce and administrative division, the courses are mostly in French, but throughout the whole of secondary school, explanations are often given in Luxembourgish. The easier level on the other hand tends not to switch to French.\n\n==Government==\nGovernment websites are primarily written in French,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gouvernement.lu/|title=gouvernement.lu - Accueil|website=www.gouvernement.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/fr/index.html|title=Luxembourg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=fr}}</ref> but there are also parts written for foreigners in other languages such as English<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/en/index.html|title=Luxembourg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103223719/http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/en/index.html|archive-date=2014-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> and German.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/de/index.html|title=Luxemburg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113135300/http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/de/index.html|archive-date=2017-01-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Luxembourg's parliament the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]], [[Bill (law)|bills]] are first written in German. Then the language of debate is in Luxembourgish, but sometimes also in French (e.g., when laws are cited). Laws are voted and codified in French. \n\nThe country's head of state, the [[Monarchy of Luxembourg|Grand-Duke]]'s website is in French,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/index.html|title=Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - Accueil|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref> however his personal Christmas speech is done in Luxembourgish<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tele.rtl.lu/emissiounen/de-journal/3026611.html|title=RTL - de Journal - Chr\u00ebschtusprooch vum Grand-Duc|date=2014-12-24|website=RTL}}</ref> ''(although a French translation is provided<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/actualites/discours/2014/12/discours-noel-fr/index.html|title=Discours de No\u00ebl prononc\u00e9 par S.A.R. le Grand-Duc (version FR) - Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - D\u00e9cembre 2014|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref>).''  In the Grand-Duke's Christmas speech in 2018 like in the past, he spoke in Luxembourgish for the most part of the speech. However when he was talking about the importance of [[Demographics of Luxembourg#Foreign population in Luxembourg|foreigners in Luxembourg]], he suddenly spoke in French as this the most used language that resident foreigners use. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/actualites/discours/2018/12/discours-noel-lu/index.html|title=Discours de No\u00ebl prononc\u00e9 par S.A.R. le Grand-Duc - Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - D\u00e9cembre 2018|date=2018-12-24|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=Luxembourgish, French|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Mass media==\nIn the written press, most newspapers such as ''[[Tageblatt]]'' and ''[[L\u00ebtzebuerger Journal]]'' are in German, while there are a few such as [[Le Quotidien (newspaper)|''Le Quotidien'']] that are in French.  On the other hand, the newspaper of record ''[[Luxemburger Wort]]'' is trilingual with most articles written in German, but also sometimes written in French and Luxembourgish, often on the same page.\n\nOn TV and on the radio, Luxembourgish is mainly used, for example the main news programme [[RTL T\u00e9l\u00e9 L\u00ebtzebuerg|RTL]]'s ''de Journal''. Spoken Luxembourgish used in news broadcasts tends to be strongly influenced by standard German in pronunciation and idiom.<ref name=\"textual\">Fernand Hoffman, \"Textual varieties of L\u00ebtzebuergesch\", in Newton, p. 219</ref> Radio broadcasters are under pressure to translate news releases sourced from German press agencies in real time and have no special training in the prose style of Luxembourgish. As a result, news tends to be superficially translated into Luxembourgish. Syntax mostly follows standard German and many words and idioms from standard German appear unmodified.<ref name=\"textual\" /> Phonology is also affected with the resulting use of intonation phrases alien to Luxembourgish.<ref name=\"developments\">Fernand Hoffman, \"L\u00ebtzebuergesch, spoken and written, developments and desirabilities\", in Newton, pp. 114 - 118</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\nIn terms of [[advertising]], which language is used depends on three factors; media, audience and origin. In written advertisements like [[billboard]]s, newspaper and magazine adverts, [[Mail order|catalogues]] and posters, the usual language of communication is French. On occasion to give a local flavour, it is written in part in Luxembourgish. [[Signage|Public signage]] is usually in French, with occasional markings in Luxembourgish, German and/or English.\n\nFor [[Advertisement film|television commercials]] broadcasting on RTL, if the advert is for an international product or service like a car or a television, it is entirely in French. However, if it is a domestic product or service like for example like [[:lb:Sources Rosport|Rosport]] mineral water or [[Luxair]], the spoken language is in Luxembourgish with the taglines in French, or less frequently in Luxembourgish or English.<ref>{{Citation|last=Sources Rosport|title=Rosport mat: Introducing Zitroun|date=2018-04-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wgUmr8BBcUM|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Luxair Luxembourg Airlines|title=Luxair commercial from 1982|date=2015-10-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W-Y07TZHfyc|language=Luxembourgish, French|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Daily use==\nGenerally, Luxembourgish is used for most day-to-day life in informal settings throughout the country. Standard German and French are reserved for formal settings, ceremonies and French in particular is commonly used in the hospitality industry. Most newspapers and printed media are in Standard German.<ref name=Hoffman>Jean-Paul Hoffman, \"L\u00ebtzebuergesch and its competitors: Language contact in Luxembourg Today\" in Newton, p. 102</ref>\n\n==Written Luxembourgish==\n\nLuxembourgish has a literary tradition that began in the 1820s with the development of serious forms of poetry, followed by drama and eventually narrative prose.<ref name=developments/> However, the average Luxembourger finds Luxembourgish texts difficult to read. Schoolchildren do not read Luxembourgish until the age of 11 or 12. Even then not all teachers adhere to the curriculum requirement to teach written Luxembourgish, some preferring to teach standard German instead, and consequently some students may not be taught written Luxembourgish. As a result, only a minority of literary-minded intellectuals find reading Luxembourgish easy or enjoyable. The majority of Luxembourgers regard their language as a spoken one only.<ref name=developments/> In recent years, the rise of texting and social media has made written Luxembourgish a lot more common between the younger generations. \n\nFor private correspondence, language choice tends to reflect social class. Members of the upper middle and upper classes tend to prefer French, although Luxembourgish may be used to convey a sense of close identification with one's nationality. German tends to be viewed negatively among the upper class, with the assumption that anyone writing in German has a poor mastery of French. Despite this, a minority of members of the upper class do prefer standard German when corresponding with close relatives. Use of German becomes more prominent the lower down the social scale one goes, followed by Luxembourgish, with French tending to be the least popular among the lower classes.<ref name=domains>Fernand Hoffman, \"The domains of L\u00ebtzebuergesch\", in Newton, pp. 134 - 135</ref>\n\nGenerally speaking, for correspondence between people who are related, standard German is preferred, followed by French and Luxembourgish equally, although social status has an influence. When people who are unrelated correspond, use of Luxembourgish drops off dramatically, and it tends not to be used at all between strangers. The choice of Luxembourgish therefore appears to reflect the closeness of the ties between the two people corresponding.<ref name=domains/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Luxembourg|Languages}}\n* [[Languages of Luxembourg]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==References==\n* DICKES, P.; BERGOZA, Guayarmina, [http://www.ceps.lu/pdf/3/art1563.pdf?CFID=46003&CFTOKEN=12740585 ''Les comp\u00e9tences linguistiques auto-attribu\u00e9es''.] '' Les cahiers du CEPS/INSTEAD, Population & Emploi'', cahier 2010-19, Septembre 2010. ISSN 2077-3048.\n* FEHLEN, F., ''BaleineBis : Une enqu\u00eate sur un march\u00e9 linguistique multilingue en profonde mutation - Luxemburgs Sprachenmarkt im Wandel''. RED N\u00b0 12, SESOPI Centre Intercommunautaire, 2009.\n* WEBER, J.J. ''Multilingualism, Education and Change'' Frankfurt, Peter Lang Verlag, 2009\n* HORNER, K. and WEBER, J.J. ''The language situation in Luxembourg'', ''Current Issues in Language Planning'' 9,1, 2008, 69-128\n* {{in lang|fr}} Projet Moien!, Sproochenhaus W\u00eblwerwoltz (Hg.), ''L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Quo Vadis? Actes du cycle de conf\u00e9rences'', Mamer: Ondine Conseil 2004\n* WEBER,N. ''The universe under the microscope: The complex linguistic situation in Luxembourg'', in De Bot, C./Kroon, S./Nelde, P./Vande Velde, H. (eds.), ''Institutional Status and use of languages in Europe'' Bonn, Asgard, 2001, 179-184\n* MAG\u00c8RE, Ph., ESMEIN, B., POTY, M., ''La situation de la langue fran\u00e7aise parmi les autres langues en usage au Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg''. Luxembourg, Centre culturel fran\u00e7ais, 1998\n* NEWTON, G. (ed.) ''Luxembourg and L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Language and Communication at the Crossroads of Europe'', Oxford, 1996\n\n{{Luxembourg topics}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Language education]]\n[[Category:Multilingualism|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2012}}\n[[Multilingualism]] is a part of everyday life for the population of [[Luxembourg]]. Legally and socially, different sectors of Luxembourg use [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], and [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]], which is a variety of [[Moselle Franconian dialects|Moselle Franconian]] with a large number of loanwords from French. Additionally, most citizens learn [[English language|English]] and may study other languages as well. A substantial immigrant population has brought numerous [[immigrant language]]s to the small state, notably [[Portuguese Luxembourger|Portuguese, which is spoken by more than one-fifth of the population]]. However, the different languages are used in different social situations.\n\n==Official languages==\nThe use of languages for legal and administrative purposes is regulated by a law promulgated in 1984, including the following provisions:<ref>{{in lang|fr}} ''M\u00e9morial A'' no. 16 (27 February 1984), pp. 196\u2013197: [http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1984/0162702/index.html \"Loi du 24 f\u00e9vrier 1984 sur le r\u00e9gime des langues\".] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060203005510/http://www.legilux.public.lu/leg/a/archives/1984/0162702/index.html |date=2006-02-03 }}</ref>\n\n* Article 1: The national language of the Luxembourgers is [[Luxembourgish language|Luxembourgish]].\n* Article 2: The laws are in [[French language|French]].\n* Article 3: The language of the government: Luxembourgish, [[German language|German]] and French can be used.\n* Article 4: Administrative questions: If a citizen asks a question in Luxembourgish, German or French, the administration must reply, as far as possible, in the language in which the question was asked.\n\nIn many other multilingual countries, such as [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]] and [[Canada]], the distribution of the languages is geographic, but in Luxembourg it is functional\u2014that is, the choice of language depends on the situation.\n\n==Education==\nAt school, all students are taught in all three official languages, although divided by age group and subject matter.  At [[primary school]], the courses are taught in German and explanations are often given in Luxembourgish.  In general, at [[secondary school]], up until the 9th grade, every subject is taught in German, except for mathematics and sciences (which are taught in French). From 10th to 13th grade, the language use depends on what level the students are in: In the more difficult level, as well as at the commerce and administrative division, the courses are mostly in French, but throughout the whole of secondary school, explanations are often given in Luxembourgish. The easier level on the other hand tends not to switch to French.\n\n==Government==\nGovernment websites are primarily written in French,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gouvernement.lu/|title=gouvernement.lu - Accueil|website=www.gouvernement.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/fr/index.html|title=Luxembourg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=fr}}</ref> but there are also parts written for foreigners in other languages such as English<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/en/index.html|title=Luxembourg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103223719/http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/en/index.html|archive-date=2014-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> and German.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/de/index.html|title=Luxemburg|access-date=2017-11-10|language=de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113135300/http://www.luxembourg.public.lu/de/index.html|archive-date=2017-01-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Luxembourg's parliament the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]], [[Bill (law)|bills]] are first written in German. Then the language of debate is in Luxembourgish, but sometimes also in French (e.g., when laws are cited). Laws are voted and codified in French. \n\nThe country's head of state, the [[Monarchy of Luxembourg|Grand-Duke]]'s website is in French,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/index.html|title=Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - Accueil|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref> however his personal Christmas speech is done in Luxembourgish<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tele.rtl.lu/emissiounen/de-journal/3026611.html|title=RTL - de Journal - Chr\u00ebschtusprooch vum Grand-Duc|date=2014-12-24|website=RTL}}</ref> ''(although a French translation is provided<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/actualites/discours/2014/12/discours-noel-fr/index.html|title=Discours de No\u00ebl prononc\u00e9 par S.A.R. le Grand-Duc (version FR) - Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - D\u00e9cembre 2014|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=fr|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref>).''  In the Grand-Duke's Christmas speech in 2018 like in the past, he spoke in Luxembourgish for the most part of the speech. However when he was talking about the importance of [[Demographics of Luxembourg#Foreign population in Luxembourg|foreigners in Luxembourg]], he suddenly spoke in French as this the most used language that resident foreigners use. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.monarchie.lu/fr/actualites/discours/2018/12/discours-noel-lu/index.html|title=Discours de No\u00ebl prononc\u00e9 par S.A.R. le Grand-Duc - Cour Grand-Ducale de Luxembourg - D\u00e9cembre 2018|date=2018-12-24|website=www.monarchie.lu|language=Luxembourgish, French|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==Mass media==\nIn the written press, most newspapers such as ''[[Tageblatt]]'' and ''[[L\u00ebtzebuerger Journal]]'' are in German, while there are a few such as [[Le Quotidien (newspaper)|''Le Quotidien'']] that are in French.  On the other hand, the newspaper of record ''[[Luxemburger Wort]]'' is trilingual with most articles written in German, but also sometimes written in French and Luxembourgish, often on the same page.\n\nOn TV and on the radio, Luxembourgish is mainly used, for example the main news programme [[RTL T\u00e9l\u00e9 L\u00ebtzebuerg|RTL]]'s ''de Journal''. Spoken Luxembourgish used in news broadcasts tends to be strongly influenced by standard German in pronunciation and idiom.<ref name=\"textual\">Fernand Hoffman, \"Textual varieties of L\u00ebtzebuergesch\", in Newton, p. 219</ref> Radio broadcasters are under pressure to translate news releases sourced from German press agencies in real time and have no special training in the prose style of Luxembourgish. As a result, news tends to be superficially translated into Luxembourgish. Syntax mostly follows standard German and many words and idioms from standard German appear unmodified.<ref name=\"textual\" /> Phonology is also affected with the resulting use of intonation phrases alien to Luxembourgish.<ref name=\"developments\">Fernand Hoffman, \"L\u00ebtzebuergesch, spoken and written, developments and desirabilities\", in Newton, pp. 114 - 118</ref>\n\n=== Advertising ===\nIn terms of [[advertising]], which language is used depends on three factors; media, audience and origin. In written advertisements like [[billboard]]s, newspaper and magazine adverts, [[Mail order|catalogues]] and posters, the usual language of communication is French. On occasion to give a local flavour, it is written in part in Luxembourgish. [[Signage|Public signage]] is usually in French, with occasional markings in Luxembourgish, German and/or English.\n\nFor [[Advertisement film|television commercials]] broadcasting on RTL, if the advert is for an international product or service like a car or a television, it is entirely in French. However, if it is a domestic product or service like for example like [[:lb:Sources Rosport|Rosport]] mineral water or [[Luxair]], the spoken language is in Luxembourgish with the taglines in French, or less frequently in Luxembourgish or English.<ref>{{Citation|last=Sources Rosport|title=Rosport mat: Introducing Zitroun|date=2018-04-16|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wgUmr8BBcUM|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Luxair Luxembourg Airlines|title=Luxair commercial from 1982|date=2015-10-15|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W-Y07TZHfyc|language=Luxembourgish, French|accessdate=2017-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Daily use==\nGenerally, Luxembourgish is used for most day-to-day life in informal settings throughout the country. Standard German and French are reserved for formal settings, ceremonies and French in particular is commonly used in the hospitality industry. Most newspapers and printed media is in Standard German.<ref name=Hoffman>Jean-Paul Hoffman, \"L\u00ebtzebuergesch and its competitors: Language contact in Luxembourg Today\" in Newton, p. 102</ref>\n\n==Written Luxembourgish==\n\nLuxembourgish has a literary tradition that began in the 1820s with the development of serious forms of poetry, followed by drama and eventually narrative prose.<ref name=developments/> However, the average Luxembourger finds Luxembourgish texts difficult to read. Schoolchildren do not read Luxembourgish until the age of 11 or 12. Even then not all teachers adhere to the curriculum requirement to teach written Luxembourgish, some preferring to teach standard German instead, and consequently some students may not be taught written Luxembourgish. As a result, only a minority of literary-minded intellectuals find reading Luxembourgish easy or enjoyable. The majority of Luxembourgers regard their language as a spoken one only.<ref name=developments/> In recent years, the rise of texting and social media has made written Luxembourgish a lot more common between the younger generations. \n\nFor private correspondence, language choice tends to reflect social class. Members of the upper middle and upper classes tend to prefer French, although Luxembourgish may be used to convey a sense of close identification with one's nationality. German tends to be viewed negatively among the upper class, with the assumption that anyone writing in German has a poor mastery of French. Despite this, a minority of members of the upper class do prefer standard German when corresponding with close relatives. Use of German becomes more prominent the lower down the social scale one goes, followed by Luxembourgish, with French tending to be the least popular among the lower classes.<ref name=domains>Fernand Hoffman, \"The domains of L\u00ebtzebuergesch\", in Newton, pp. 134 - 135</ref>\n\nGenerally speaking, for correspondence between people who are related, standard German is preferred, followed by French and Luxembourgish equally, although social status has an influence. When people who are unrelated correspond, use of Luxembourgish drops off dramatically, and it tends not to be used at all between strangers. The choice of Luxembourgish therefore appears to reflect the closeness of the ties between the two people corresponding.<ref name=domains/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Luxembourg|Languages}}\n* [[Languages of Luxembourg]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==References==\n* DICKES, P.; BERGOZA, Guayarmina, [http://www.ceps.lu/pdf/3/art1563.pdf?CFID=46003&CFTOKEN=12740585 ''Les comp\u00e9tences linguistiques auto-attribu\u00e9es''.] '' Les cahiers du CEPS/INSTEAD, Population & Emploi'', cahier 2010-19, Septembre 2010. ISSN 2077-3048.\n* FEHLEN, F., ''BaleineBis : Une enqu\u00eate sur un march\u00e9 linguistique multilingue en profonde mutation - Luxemburgs Sprachenmarkt im Wandel''. RED N\u00b0 12, SESOPI Centre Intercommunautaire, 2009.\n* WEBER, J.J. ''Multilingualism, Education and Change'' Frankfurt, Peter Lang Verlag, 2009\n* HORNER, K. and WEBER, J.J. ''The language situation in Luxembourg'', ''Current Issues in Language Planning'' 9,1, 2008, 69-128\n* {{in lang|fr}} Projet Moien!, Sproochenhaus W\u00eblwerwoltz (Hg.), ''L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Quo Vadis? Actes du cycle de conf\u00e9rences'', Mamer: Ondine Conseil 2004\n* WEBER,N. ''The universe under the microscope: The complex linguistic situation in Luxembourg'', in De Bot, C./Kroon, S./Nelde, P./Vande Velde, H. (eds.), ''Institutional Status and use of languages in Europe'' Bonn, Asgard, 2001, 179-184\n* MAG\u00c8RE, Ph., ESMEIN, B., POTY, M., ''La situation de la langue fran\u00e7aise parmi les autres langues en usage au Grand-Duch\u00e9 de Luxembourg''. Luxembourg, Centre culturel fran\u00e7ais, 1998\n* NEWTON, G. (ed.) ''Luxembourg and L\u00ebtzebuergesch: Language and Communication at the Crossroads of Europe'', Oxford, 1996\n\n{{Luxembourg topics}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Language education]]\n[[Category:Multilingualism|*]]\n", "name_user": "2dk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDaily use", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multilingualism_in_Luxembourg"}
{"title_page": "Megaceroides algericus", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|Late Pleistocene|Holocene}}\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| parent_authority = Joleaud, 1914\n| taxon = Megaceroides algericus\n| species = \n| authority = Lydekker, 1890\n| synonyms = ''Cervus pachygenys'' <small>Pomel, 1892</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Megaceroides algericus''''' is an extinct species of deer known from the Late Pleistocene to Holocene of North Africa. It is one of only two species of deer known to have ever inhabited the African continent, alongside the [[Barbary stag]], a subspecies of [[Red deer]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe species was first described by [[Richard Lydekker]] as ''Cervus algericus'' in 1890 from a maxilla with teeth found near [[Hammam Maskhoutine]] in Algeria. The species ''Cervus pachygenys'' was erected for a [[Pachyostosis|pachyostotic]] mandible and an isolated molar from the Algerian Neolithic by [[Auguste Pomel]] in 1892. L\u00e9once Joleaud in two publications in 1914 and 1916 synonymised the two species, and suggested affinities with the giant deer of Europe like ''[[Megaloceros]],'' and placed it in the newly erected [[subgenus]] '''''Megaceroides'''.'' [[Camille Arambourg]] in publications in 1932 and 1938 raised ''Megaceroides'' to the full genus rank, and described additional cranial material, which were figured but not described in detail.\n\nIn 1953 Augusto Azzaroli published a systematic taxonomy for ''Megaloceros'', he avoided using the name ''Megaceroides'', and suggested affinities to the proposed \"''verticornis'' group\", and noted its simiarities to ''[[Sinomegaceros pachyosteus]].'' The taxonomic relationships of giant deer and their smaller insular relatives are unresolved, it was considered belong to ''Megaloceros'' by Hadjouis in 1990 with ''Megaceroides'' at subgenus rank.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hadjouis|first=Djillali|date=1990|title=Megaceroides algericus (Lydekker, 1890), du gisement des Phacoch\u00e8res (Alger, Alg\u00e9rie). Etude critique de la position syst\u00e9matique de Megaceroides|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.3406/quate.1990.1941|journal=Quaternaire|volume=1|issue=3|pages=247\u2013258|doi=10.3406/quate.1990.1941|issn=1142-2904}}</ref> Its affinities with ''Megaloceros'' are well supported by morphological similarities. A comprehensive description of the taxon published in 2015 suggested that it originated from ''Megaloceros mugarensis'' from the Middle Pleistocene of the Levant, with Middle Pleistocene cervid remains from North Africa possibly belonging to an ancestor of the species, and retained ''Megaceroides'' at generic rank.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Croitor|first=Roman|date=July\u2013September 2016|title=Systematical position and paleoecology of the endemic deer Megaceroides algericus Lydekker, 1890 (Cervidae, Mammalia) from the late Pleistocene-early Holocene of North Africa|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304812764_Systematical_position_and_paleoecology_of_the_endemic_deer_Megaceroides_algericus_Lydekker_1890_Cervidae_Mammalia_from_the_late_Pleistocene-early_Holocene_of_North_Africa|journal=Geobios|language=en|volume=49|issue=4|pages=265\u2013283|doi=10.1016/j.geobios.2016.05.002|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe species was found within the vicinity of the [[Atlas Mountains]], with most localities located within the Algerian Atlas, with one find being in lowland Morocco near [[Tit Mellil]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe species is known from limited material, and knowledge of post-cranial remains and antlers are poor. The estimated size of the animal is smaller than a red deer but slightly larger than a [[fallow deer]]. It is known from a mostly complete skull of an aged individual with worn teeth found near [[A\u00efn B\u00e9nian, Algiers|A\u00efn B\u00e9nian]] in Algeria, alongside other fragmentary crania. The skull is broad, but the length of the skull (specifically the [[splanchnocranium]]) is relatively short, a morphology that is unknown in other deer species. The two halves of the mandible are estimated to have had a contact angle of 60 degrees. The skull and dentary exhibit extreme thickening ([[pachyostosis]]) somewhat similar to that in ''Megaloceros'', except that the [[vomer]] and zygomatic bar are unaffected, the pachyostosis is among the most extreme of any known mammal. The upper canines are absent and the lower fourth premolar (P<small>4</small>) is molarised. The preserved antler is cylindrical in cross section, and orientated predomiantly anteriorly, laterally and slightly dorsally, the antler becomes flattened distally.\n\n== Ecology ==\nThe ecology of the species is unclear owing to the lack of living analogues for its unique morphology. On several morphological grounds, it has been proposed that its habits were semi or periaquatic, with the weak mastication ability and polished cheek teeth by attrition suggesting a preference for soft water plants, with taking of non-aquatic forage during the dry seasons. The extreme pachyostosis has been suggested to have been a protection against attacks by crocodiles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Extinction ==\nMost of the remains assigned to the species are known from [[Paleolithic|Palaeolithic]] archaeological sites, suggesting they were hunted by people. The last known date for the species dates between 6641 and 6009 cal BP, during the [[Neolithic]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fernandez|first=Philippe|last2=Bouzouggar|first2=Abdeljalil|last3=Collina-Girard|first3=Jacques|last4=Coulon|first4=Mathieu|date=July 2015|title=The last occurrence of Megaceroides algericus Lyddekker, 1890 (Mammalia, Cervidae) during the middle Holocene in the cave of Bizmoune (Morocco, Essaouira region)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S104061821500230X|journal=Quaternary International|language=en|volume=374|pages=154\u2013167|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2015.03.034}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cenozoic mammals of Africa]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene even-toed ungulates]]\n[[Category:Holocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1890]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| fossil_range = {{fossil range|Late Pleistocene|Holocene}}\n| image = \n| image_caption = \n| parent_authority = Joleaud, 1914\n| taxon = Megaceroides algericus\n| species = \n| authority = Lydekker, 1890\n| synonyms = ''Cervus pachygenys'' <small>Pomel, 1892</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Megaceroides algericus''''' is an extinct species of deer known from the Late Pleistocene to Holocene of North Africa. It is one of only two species of deer known to have ever inhabited the African continent, alongside the [[Barbary stag]], a subspecies of [[Red deer]].\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe species was first described by [[Richard Lydekker]] as ''Cervus algericus'' in 1890 from a maxilla with teeth found near [[Hammam Maskhoutine]] in Algeria. The species ''Cervus pachygenys'' was erected for a [[Pachyostosis|pachyostotic]] mandible and an isolated molar from the Algerian Neolithic by [[Auguste Pomel]] in 1892. L\u00e9once Joleaud in two publications in 1914 and 1916 synonymised the two species, and suggested affinities with the giant deer of Europe like ''[[Megaloceros]],'' and placed it in the newly erected [[subgenus]] '''''Megaceroides'''.'' [[Camille Arambourg]] in publications in 1932 and 1938 raised ''Megaceroides'' to the full genus rank, and described additional cranial material, which were figured but not described in detail.\n\nIn 1953 Augusto Azzaroli published a systematic taxonomy for ''Megaloceros'', he avoided using the name ''Megaceroides'', and suggested affinities to the proposed \"''verticornis'' group\", and noted its simiarities to ''[[Sinomegaceros pachyosteus]].'' The taxonomic relationships of giant deer and their smaller insular relatives are unresolved, it was considered belong to ''Megaloceros'' by Hadjouis in 1990 with ''Megaceroides'' at subgenus rank.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hadjouis|first=Djillali|date=1990|title=Megaceroides algericus (Lydekker, 1890), du gisement des Phacoch\u00e8res (Alger, Alg\u00e9rie). Etude critique de la position syst\u00e9matique de Megaceroides|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.3406/quate.1990.1941|journal=Quaternaire|volume=1|issue=3|pages=247\u2013258|doi=10.3406/quate.1990.1941|issn=1142-2904}}</ref> Its affinities with ''Megaloceros'' are well supported by morphological similarities. A comprehensive description of the taxon published in 2015 suggested that it originated from ''Megaloceros mugarensis'' from the Middle Pleistocene of the Levant, with Middle Pleistocene cervid remains from North Africa possibly belonging to an ancestor of the species, and retained ''Megaceroides'' at generic rank.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Croitor|first=Roman|date=2016-07|title=Systematical position and paleoecology of the endemic deer Megaceroides algericus Lydekker, 1890 (Cervidae, Mammalia) from the late Pleistocene-early Holocene of North Africa|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/304812764_Systematical_position_and_paleoecology_of_the_endemic_deer_Megaceroides_algericus_Lydekker_1890_Cervidae_Mammalia_from_the_late_Pleistocene-early_Holocene_of_North_Africa|journal=Geobios|language=en|volume=49|issue=4|pages=265\u2013283|doi=10.1016/j.geobios.2016.05.002|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe species was found within the vicinity of the [[Atlas Mountains]], with most localities located within the Algerian Atlas, with one find being in lowland Morocco near [[Tit Mellil]].\n\n== Description ==\nThe species is known from limited material, and knowledge of post-cranial remains and antlers are poor. The estimated size of the animal is smaller than a red deer but slightly larger than a [[fallow deer]]. It is known from a mostly complete skull of an aged individual with worn teeth found near [[A\u00efn B\u00e9nian, Algiers|A\u00efn B\u00e9nian]] in Algeria, alongside other fragmentary crania. The skull is broad, but the length of the skull (specifically the [[splanchnocranium]]) is relatively short, a morphology that is unknown in other deer species. The two halves of the mandible are estimated to have had a contact angle of 60 degrees. The skull and dentary exhibit extreme thickening ([[pachyostosis]]) somewhat similar to that in ''Megaloceros'', except that the [[vomer]] and zygomatic bar are unaffected, the pachyostosis is among the most extreme of any known mammal. The upper canines are absent and the lower fourth premolar (P<small>4</small>) is molarised. The preserved antler is cylindrical in cross section, and orientated predomiantly anteriorly, laterally and slightly dorsally, the antler becomes flattened distally.\n\n== Ecology ==\nThe ecology of the species is unclear owing to the lack of living analogues for its unique morphology. On several morphological grounds, it has been proposed that its habits were semi or periaquatic, with the weak mastication ability and polished cheek teeth by attrition suggesting a preference for soft water plants, with taking of non-aquatic forage during the dry seasons. The extreme pachyostosis has been suggested to have been a protection against attacks by crocodiles.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Extinction ==\nMost of the remains assigned to the species are known from [[Paleolithic|Palaeolithic]] archaeological sites, suggesting they were hunted by people. The last known date for the species dates between 6641 and 6009 cal BP, during the [[Neolithic]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fernandez|first=Philippe|last2=Bouzouggar|first2=Abdeljalil|last3=Collina-Girard|first3=Jacques|last4=Coulon|first4=Mathieu|date=2015-07|title=The last occurrence of Megaceroides algericus Lyddekker, 1890 (Mammalia, Cervidae) during the middle Holocene in the cave of Bizmoune (Morocco, Essaouira region)|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S104061821500230X|journal=Quaternary International|language=en|volume=374|pages=154\u2013167|doi=10.1016/j.quaint.2015.03.034}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Cenozoic mammals of Africa]]\n[[Category:Pleistocene even-toed ungulates]]\n[[Category:Holocene extinctions]]\n[[Category:Fossil taxa described in 1890]]\n", "name_user": "Lord Bolingbroke", "label": "safe", "comment": "reformat date values to resolvea CS1 error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Megaceroides_algericus"}
{"title_page": "Garbalia", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=November 2018}}\n{{original research|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Garbalia\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = Rural Area\n| pushpin_map                     = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|22.632568|N|88.113055|E|display==inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|States]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of West Bengal|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Howrah District|Howrah]]\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_footnotes         = \n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 711410\n| area_code                       = 913214\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone Code\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-WB]]\n| registration_plate              = WB-xx xxx\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]]\nconstituency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Sreerampur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Sreerampur]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Jagatballavpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Jagatballavpur]]\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 8\n| elevation_ft                    = \n| blank_name                      = Literacy Rate\n| blank_info                      = 83.85%\n| website                         = {{URL|howrah.gov.in/}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n| demographics1_info1             = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]]\n}}\n'''Garbalia''' is a rural area located in the [[Howrah]] district of [[West Bengal]], [[India]]. It is a part of the [[Jagatballavpur]] bloc in the [[Howrah Sadar subdivision]] in the north-eastern part of the [[Howrah]]. Garbalia is 30&nbsp;km from the state's capital, [[Kolkata]]. Garbalia along with its 11 other neighbouring villages - Ichhapur, Tripurapur, Kumarpur, North Sealdanga, South Sealdanga, Jamunabalia, Badebalia, Ranmahal, Nimabalia, Nijbalia and Pratappur are together called greater Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pincodeindia.net/state/west-bengal.html|title=West Bengal - List of District, Village, Population & Literacy|website=www.pincodeindia.net|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> \n\nGarbalia is located at {{coord|22.632568|N|88.113055|E|}}. The PIN code of Garbalia is 711410.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/pincode/india/west-bengal/howrah/|title=Pin Code of Howrah in West Bengal, Howrah Postal Code|website=www.mapsofindia.com|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nGarbalia is connected with  [[Grand Trunk Road]] by Howrah-Amta Road and it is also connected with  [[Kona Expressway]] (Mumbai-Kolkata Highway) by Pantihal-Dhulagarh Road. Garbalia is connected with [[South Eastern Railway zone|South-Eastern Railway]] by Howrah-Amta Local Railway.\n \n===Minibus===\n*15 [[Howrah]]-Khanderghat [[Minibus|minibuses]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transport.wb.gov.in/|title=Home|website=Transport Department, Government of West Bengal|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n \n===Train===\n[[Howrah]]-[[Amta]] Local (From Pantihal, Munshirhat or Bargachia Station). Garbalia is approximately 3.1 km away from [[Pantihal railway station|Pantihal railway station,]] 4.0 km away from [[Munsirhat railway station]] and 7.0 km away from [[Bargachia railway station]].\n \n[[Munsirhat|Munshirhat]]-[[Sankrail]] trekker route and numerous others tranportation systems are also available in Garbalia.\n \n==Education==\nGarbalia Rakhal Chandra Manna Institution (Estd-1937) is the only higher secondary School in Balia Pargana and second oldest secondary and oldest higher secondary school in Jagatballavpur Block. There is also a secondary girl's school in Balia Pargana-Garbalia Girl's High School. Both schools are located at Ichapur. There are also numerous Primary Schools in Balia Pargana. The nearest college is [[Sovarani Memorial College]] which is located at [[Jagatballavpur (community development block)|Jagatballavpur.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schools.org.in/west-bengal|title=Schools in West Bengal {{!}} List of Schools in 21 Districts of West Bengal|website=schools.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Culture==\n[[Devi|Singhabahini]] [[Temple]] (located at Nizbalia Market Area), Buripukur [[Kali]] [[Temple]](located at Ichhapur) are two most religious cultural hotspots in Balia Pargana.\n \n==Healthcare facilities==\nThe nearest primary block level hospital is located at [[Jagatballavpur]]. Numerous other rural health centers and medicine stores are also present in Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/pages/search_hospitals|title=Welcome to WB HEALTH Portal|website=www.wbhealth.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Market==\nThere are mainly two markets located in Balia Pargana. The first is located in Nizbalia and called \"Bele Bazar\".It is the biggest and key marketplace in Balia Pargana.The second market is located at Khanderghat-Nimabalia area.\n \n==Post Offices==\nBalia Pargana consists of three [[post office]]s, which are- Garbalia, Nijbalia and Sealdanga. Among them the Nizbalia [[post office]] belongs to Pantihal  [[Panchayat]] and the rests belong to Sealdanga  [[Panchayat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/sites/PostalCircles/WestBengal/Pages/cpio.aspx|title=Center Public Information Officers|website=www.indiapost.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n \n==Banking Facility==\nThere are now total 4 [[bank]]s in the Balia Pargana. One of them is [[Indian Overseas Bank]] which is located at Ichapur and rests are local Govt. owned or private rural [[bank]]s. There are also several others [[Automated teller machine|ATM]] facility located in Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.mapsofindia.com/bank-branches/indian_overseas_bank/west_bengal/|title=Indian Overseas Bank West Bengal IFSC Code,Indian Overseas Bank Branches in West Bengal|website=business.mapsofindia.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Festivals==\nGarbalia or Balia Pargana is famous for \"[[Kali Puja|Kalipuja]]\" or [[Diwali]] festival.\"[[Durga Puja|Durgapuja]]\",\"[[Saraswati puja|Swaraswatipuja]]\", \"[[Christmas]]\" ,\"[[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]]\", \"[[Holi]]\" are also quiet popular in Balia Pargana. Both [[Pahela Baishakh|Bengali new year]] or [[Pahela Baishakh]] and [[New Year's Eve]] are celebrated in Balia Pargana. National holidays like [[Independence Day (India)|Independance Day]], [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]] and [[Gandhi Jayanti]] and birthdays of famous national heroes are also celebrated in Balia Pargana. Various other local festivals and fairs also take places in Balia Pargana which draw huge crowds.<ref>Santra, Tarapada and Bandopadhyay, Amiya Kumar, ''Howrah Jelar Purakirti'' (in Bengali), pp. 115\u2013116, Government of West Bengal</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n1.^ Santra, Tarapada and Bandopadhyay, Amiya Kumar, ''Howrah Jelar Purakirti'' (in Bengali), pp.&nbsp;115\u2013116, Government of West Bengal\n2.[https://www.indiatvnews.com/pincode/west-bengal/howrah/garbalia ^https://www.indiatvnews.com/pincode/west-bengal/howrah/garbalia]\n3.[http://wikimapia.org/553473/Garbalia-Rakhalchandra-Manna-Institution ^ http://wikimapia.org/553473/Garbalia-Rakhalchandra-Manna-Institution]\n\n{{Howrah District}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Howrah district]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=November 2018}}\n{{original research|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Garbalia\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = Rural Area\n| pushpin_map                     = India West Bengal#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|22.632568|N|88.113055|E|display==inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|States]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of West Bengal|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Howrah District|Howrah]]\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_footnotes         = \n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 711410\n| area_code                       = 913214\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone Code\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-WB]]\n| registration_plate              = WB-xx xxx\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]]\nconstituency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Sreerampur (Lok Sabha constituency)|Sreerampur]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Jagatballavpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Jagatballavpur]]\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 8\n| elevation_ft                    = \n| blank_name                      = Literacy Rate\n| blank_info                      = 83.85%\n| website                         = {{URL|howrah.gov.in/}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n| demographics1_info1             = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]]\n}}\n'''Garbalia''' is a rural area located in the [[Howrah]] district of [[West Bengal]], [[India]]. It is a part of the [[Jagatballavpur]] bloc in the [[Howrah Sadar subdivision]] in the north-eastern part of the [[Howrah]]. Garbalia is 30&nbsp;km from the state's capital, [[Kolkata]]. Garbalia along with its 11 other neighbouring villages - Ichhapur, Tripurapur, Kumarpur, North Sealdanga, South Sealdanga, Jamunabalia, Badebalia, Ranmahal, Nimabalia, Nijbalia and Pratappur are together called greater Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pincodeindia.net/state/west-bengal.html|title=West Bengal - List of District, Village, Population & Literacy|website=www.pincodeindia.net|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> \n\nGarbalia is located at {{coord|22.632568|N|88.113055|E|}}. The PIN code of Garbalia is 711410.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mapsofindia.com/pincode/india/west-bengal/howrah/|title=Pin Code of Howrah in West Bengal, Howrah Postal Code|website=www.mapsofindia.com|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nGarbalia is connected with  [[Grand Trunk Road]] by Howrah-Amta Road and it is also connected with  [[Kona Expressway]] (Mumbai-Kolkata Highway) by Pantihal-Dhulagarh Road. Garbalia is connected with [[South Eastern Railway zone|South-Eastern Railway]] by Howrah-Amta Local Railway.\n \n===Minibus===\n*15 [[Howrah]]-Khanderghat [[Minibus|minibuses]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transport.wb.gov.in/|title=Home|website=Transport Department, Government of West Bengal|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n \n===Train===\n[[Howrah]]-[[Amta]] Local (From Pantihal, Munshirhat or Bargachia Station). Garbalia is approximately 3.1 km away from [[Pantihal railway station|Pantihal railway station,]] 4.0 km away from [[Munsirhat railway station]] and 7.0 km away from [[Bargachia railway station]].\n \n[[Munsirhat|Munshirhat]]-[[Sankrail]] trekker route and numerous others tranportation systems are also available in Garbalia.\n \n==Education==\nGarbalia Rakhal Chandra Manna Institution (Estd-1937) is the only higher secondary School in Balia Pargana and second oldest secondary and oldest higher secondary school in Jagatballavpur Block. There is also a secondary girl's school in Balia Pargana-Garbalia Girl's High School. Both schools are located at Ichapur. There are also numerous Primary Schools in Balia Pargana. The nearest college is [[Sovarani Memorial College]] which is located at [[Jagatballavpur (community development block)|Jagatballavpur.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://schools.org.in/west-bengal|title=Schools in West Bengal {{!}} List of Schools in 21 Districts of West Bengal|website=schools.org.in|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Culture==\n[[Devi|Singhabahini]] [[Temple]] (located at Nizbalia Market Area), Buripukur [[Kali]] [[Temple]](located at Ichhapur) are two most religious cultural hotspots in Balia Pargana.\n \n==Healthcare facilities==\nThe nearest primary block level hospital is located at [[Jagatballavpur]]. Numerous other rural health centers and medicine stores are also present in Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/pages/search_hospitals|title=Welcome to WB HEALTH Portal|website=www.wbhealth.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Market==\nThere are mainly two markets located in Balia Pargana. The first is located in Nizbalia and called \"Bele Bazar\".It is the biggest and key marketplace in Balia Pargana.The second market is located at Khanderghat-Nimabalia area.\n \n==Post Offices==\nBalia Pargana consists of three [[post office]]s, which are- Garbalia, Nijbalia and Sealdanga. Among them the Nizbalia [[post office]] belongs to Pantihal  [[Panchayat]] and the rests belong to Sealdanga  [[Panchayat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/sites/PostalCircles/WestBengal/Pages/cpio.aspx|title=Center Public Information Officers|website=www.indiapost.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n \n==Banking Facility==\nThere are now total 4 [[bank]]s in the Balia Pargana. One of them is [[Indian Overseas Bank]] which is located at Ichapur and rests are local Govt. owned or private rural [[bank]]s. There are also several others [[Automated teller machine|ATM]] facility located in Balia Pargana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://business.mapsofindia.com/bank-branches/indian_overseas_bank/west_bengal/|title=Indian Overseas Bank West Bengal IFSC Code,Indian Overseas Bank Branches in West Bengal|website=business.mapsofindia.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n \n==Festivals==\nGarbalia or Balia Pargana is famous for \"[[Kali Puja|Kalipuja]]\" or [[Diwali]] festival.\"[[Durga Puja|Durgapuja]]\",\"[[Saraswati puja|Swaraswatipuja]]\", \"[[Christmas]]\" ,\"[[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]]\", \"[[Holi]]\" are also quiet popular in Balia Pargana.Numerous other local festivals and fairs also take places in Balia Pargana which draw huge crowds. <ref>Santra, Tarapada and Bandopadhyay, Amiya Kumar, ''Howrah Jelar Purakirti'' (in Bengali), pp. 115\u2013116, Government of West Bengal</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n1.^ Santra, Tarapada and Bandopadhyay, Amiya Kumar, ''Howrah Jelar Purakirti'' (in Bengali), pp.&nbsp;115\u2013116, Government of West Bengal\n2.[https://www.indiatvnews.com/pincode/west-bengal/howrah/garbalia ^https://www.indiatv